s -- tDialogue Six. With Kierkegaard in Africa -- tJoint Statement -- tSelf, Hope, and the Unconditional: Kierkegaard on Faith and Hope -- tKierkegaard in West Africa: Hope and Sacrifi ce in a Ghanaian Fishing Village -- tReferences -- tEpilogue. Anthropology and Philosophy in Dialogue? -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe present book is no ordinary anthology, but rather a workroom in which anthropologists and philosophers initiate a dialogue on trust and hope, two important topics for both fields of study. The book combines work between scholars from different universities in the U.S. and Denmark. Thus, besides bringing the two disciplines in dialogue, it also cuts across differences in national contexts and academic style. The interdisciplinary efforts of the contributors demonstrate how such a collaboration can result in new and challenging ways of thinking about trust and hope. Reading the dialogues may, therefore, also inspire others to work in the productive intersection between anthropology and philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aHope. 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 0aTrust. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBubandt, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalsgård, Anne Line, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalsgård, Anne Line, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJackson, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensen, Uffe Juul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlausen, Søren Harnow, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aL